{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_greenville_ver01/data/sn95047212/00529042334/1958061901/0117.xml":{"full_text":"t'Toivle I\ni 'Talks:\nj\nCHAS. F. TOWLE I\nPublisher\n\u201cClerk\u2019s Mail, a publication of\nthe P.O. clerks, \u201cSoundwaves,\u201d of\nthe Communication Workers and\na half dozen other lesser publica-\ntions in the Miami\narea are legitimate,\nwell-edited and cir-\n\u201cLABOR\nPAPERS\u201d\nculated labor papers,\ndealing specifically with affairs\nof their own unions. With them,\nthe Labor Citizen has no quarrel.\nThey are doing a good job with\nin the confines of their own in\ndividual unions, and we commend\nthem each and every one for\nthe job they are doing. The\nLabor Citizen, as the official organ\nof the Dade County Federation of\nLabor, the Miami Building Trades\nCouncil and the Florida Federated\nLabor Council, AFL-CIO, has a\nmuch broader field to cover.\nHowever, there are publications\nin this area, and one in particular,\nwhich pounce ghoulishly upon any\nexcuse to use the cloak of labor for\ntheir own particular profit. The\nsheet to which we refer not only\ndoes not even patronize a union\nprinter, but it has no standing as a\nlegal newspaper, does not publish\nregularly, and uses high-pressure,\nblack-jack methods to blacken the\nname of labor in this vicinity. And\nas we write this they are calling\nunion contractors on the phone and\nsoliciting advertising for a \u201cSalute\nto Labor\u201d Edition, which if they\nrun true to form will probably not\nbe printed before Christmas.\nThe function of the legitimate\nlabor press is well-defined in a\nsituation of this kind\u2014to expose\nthe \u201cphonies\u201d wherever we find\nthem, and to advise the advertis\ning public as to how they can help\nsuppress this kind of a parasite.\nJust remember, when you are ap\nproached on the telephone for ad\nvertising, ask to see the latest copy\nof \u201cthe paper; whether it is printed\nin a union shop; by what labor\nunions it is endorsed, and the name\nof the editor and publisher. This\ninformation will enable you to\njudge as to w r hether it is a legiti\nmate enterprise or just another\nracket sheet.\nDeauville Admits\nUnion Exists\nMorris Lansburgh\u2019s Deauville\nHotel, which has fought the efforts\nof Local 255, Hotel Employees Un\nion, AFL-CIO, to organize its\nworkers, has agreed to arbitration\nof its dispute with the union.\nThe dispute, which is now before\nthe courts, will be arbitrated by\nthe Rabbinical Council of America.\nNo date for the arbitration hear\nings has been set but they prob\nably will take place on Miami\nBeach early next month.\nDavid Herman, president of\nLocal 255, said the rabbinical\ngroup had been inclined to cancel\nits convention scheduled to begin\nJuly 7 in the Deauville, because\nof the union-management dispute.\nHowever, the council decided in\nstead to \u201coffer its good offices to\narbitrate the differences,\u201d Her\nman said.\nThe council offered both sides to\nsubmit the dispute to arbitration\nand both agreed. Local 255 has\nsigned and submitted a formal\nagreement to the council submit\nting the dispute to arbitration.\nHolland Amendment\nSnowed Under\nThe amendment to the Wage\nand Hour Law which Florida\u2019s\nSenator Spessard Holland tried to\nput over and which would have\nbeen a boon to \u201cright-to-wreck\u201d\nlaw states and poison to all utili\nties workers, met a just fate at the\nhands of the Senate. By a sizeable\nmajority the Senate voted against\nthis insidious amendment. How\never, that doesn\u2019t lessen in the\nleast the enormity of the offense\nof the Senator in the eyes of or\nganized labor in Florida. Never in\nthe years he has been in the Sen\nate has he been definitely on the\nside of the working man.\nLabor (Citizen\nOfficial Organ of DADE COUNTY FEDERATION OF LABOR,\nBUILDING TRADES COUNCIL, FLORIDA STATE FEDERATED LABOR COUNCIL, AFL-CIO\nVol. XXXX\u2014No. 9\nNOTICE\nTo All Business Agents and Union Contractors:\nIt has come to our attention the the publication\nknown as the Florida Free Press is sol .ting advertising\nfrom union contractors for a \u201cSalute to Labor\u201d edition,\ntime of publication as yet undecided. This publication\nis printed in a NON-UNION SHOP, and to the best in\nformation available, has no subscription list nor regular\ndate of publication. The latest copy of the publication\nof which we have knowledge was last printed around\nChristmas, and contained ads solicited for a Labor Day\nedition as well as for Christmas. The Florida Free Press\nhas no connection with organized labor and if they make\nsuch claims in their sales talk it is a misrepresentation\nof facts. The Labor Citizen is the only publication in\nDade County which is officially endorsed by the Dade\nCounty Federation of Labor, the Miami Building Trades\nCouncil and the Florida State Federated Labor Council,\nAFL-CIO.\nThis letter from President Owens of the Dade\nCounty Federation of Labor will further clarify the posi\ntion of the Labor Citizen.\nJune 18, 1958\nMr. Charles Towle, Publisher\nLabor Citizen\n4314 N. W. 7th Ave.\nMiami, Florida\nDear Charlie:\nThis is to reaffirm the position of the Dade County\nFederation of Labor in respect to your paper, the Labor\nCitizen.\nAt the present time the Labor Citizen is the only paper\nin Dade County which carries the endorsement of the\nDade County Federation of Labor.\nIt is recognized as the medium by which the Dade\nCounty Federation of Labor can get its message to the\nmembers of organized labor in this area.\nWith kindest personal regards,\nW. J. Owens, President\nCommunity Services Sets\nProgram to Aid Jobless\nMeeting in the shadow of the current recession, 300\nAFL-CIO Community Services staff members and volun\nteers explored effective ways of assisting the unemployed\nat a week-long conference at Washington\u2019s Shoreham\nHotel.\nLeo Perlis, director of Commun\nity Service Activities for the AFL\nCIO, sounded the keynote when\nhe declared: \u201cOur primary task\u2014\nworking with the voluntary and\ntax-supported agencies in the\nhealth, welfare and recreation\nfield is to help the jobless work\ner maintain as high a level of eco\nnomic security as is possible, and\nto help minimize the emotional and\nphysical crisis that accompanies\nthe tragedy of unemployment.\u201d\nHere is the basic 10-point pro\ngram for aiding the unemployed\naround which the conference was\nbuilt:\nInforming the jobless worker\nthat the labor movement has a plan\nto help with personal problems.\nEstablishing a system where\nby union counsellors are on duty\nat union headquarters.\nProtection of unemployment\ncompensation claims by acquaint\ning workers with the procedure for\nfiling, and in some instances set\nting up auxiliary branches of un\nemployment compensation offices\nat union halls.\nProviding jobless workers\nwith details of obtaining supple\nmental unemployment benefits\nwhere available under union con\ntracts.\nFinding public welfare sources\nof food, shelter, clothing and medi\ncal care where compensation is ex\nhausted, checks are delayed, claims\nare disallowed or the amount is\ntoo small.\nGetting welfare officials to\nrelax usual eligibility requirements\n(Continued on Page 3)\nMiami, Florida, Thursday, June I^, 1958\nClothing Workers\nHave Booth At\nCWA Convention\nThe Amalgamated Clothing\nWorkers Union of America par\nticipated in the convention of the\nC.W.A. with an exhibit on Union\nLabels. For several years the Am\nalgamated Clothing Workers Un\nion has been conducting a nation\nwide union label campaign to make\nunion members and the general\npublic aware of the importance of\npurchasing union made wearing\napparel as well as supporting all\nunion made products and services.\nMrs. Hazel Moses, the South\neastern Union Label Director of\nthe Amalgamated Clothing Work\ners of America, assisted by Frieda\nBrabdorff, conducted the conven\ntion exhibit and gave away as\nprizes a man\u2019s suit of clothes and\na box of (3) men\u2019s shirts. Dele\ngates registered for a chance at\nthe prizes by displaying a union\nlabel on their clothing, while at\ntending the convention. Literature\nwas also plentiful for the delegates\nto take back to their local unions.\nMany requests for further infor\nmation on the campaign were\ntaken to be mailed directly to the\nlocal unions.\nPresident Beirne of the C.W.A.\nstated that all C.W.A. locals would\nreceive a list of NON-UNION prod\nucts from the national office of\nC.W.A. after the convention.\nWingo Shirts are non-union.\nCWA Convention\nScores President\nFor Inaction\nMiami Beach\u2014A multi-pronged anti-recession pro\ngram was hammered out bj r 3.000 delegates and alternates\nto the 20th anniversary convention of the Communications\nWorkers of America.\nMeeting at Municipal Auditorium, the convention\nadopted a series of resolutions*\ncalling for positive federal action\nto halt the economic downturn and\nflaying the Eisenhower Adminis\ntration for having \u201cdeviated from\nthe basic principles\u201d of taxation\nby shifting the burden to low and\nmoderate income families.\nIn addition to recommending\ntax relief for low and middle-in\ncome families and repeal of deple\ntion allowances for major oil com-\nPlumbers Hold\nBiennial Election\nPlumbers Local Union No. 519\nwill hold their biennial election\nThursday, June 26th at the hall,\n2409 N.W. 17th Avenue. The polls\nwill be open from 4 to 9 p.m. In\naccordance with the U.A. Consti\ntution all members must be pres\nent to vote. There are no absentee\nballots. A new ruling permits ap\nprentices to vote in this election.\nCandidates for the various of\nfices are as follows:\nPresident (Vote for One)\nM. C. (Mike) Mathis\nFred Wells (Incumbent)\nVice President (Vote for One)\nG. T. (George) Fitzpatrick\n(Incumbent)\nHenry J. Passing\nBusiness Manager (Vote for Ore)\nO. D. (Bud) Bennett (Incumbent)\nJ. J. (Jack) Buckard\nW. J. (Bill) Ringemann\nBusiness Agents (Vote for Two)\nGeorge Nash, Sr. (Incumbent)\nD. T. (Dave) Dobbs (Incumbent)\nS. W. (Sam) Long\nC. (Chas.) Wickerman\nR. W. (Bob) Allen\nFinancial Secretary\n(Vote for One)\nN. (Nate) Goldy\nD. E. (Don) Sparks\nRecording Secretary\n(Vote for One)\nO. (Ollie) Branconier\nInside Guard (Vote for One)\nA. (Aaron) Kayfetz\nExecutive Board (Vote for Four)\nS. (Tony) Bertoni, (Incumbent)\nS. M. (Sam) Bloom (Incumbent)\nE. C. (Ed) Petersen\nJ. E. (Jack) McCarthy\nJ. G. (John) Ford (Incumbent)\nE. (Gene) Martin (Incumbent\nFinance Committee (Vote for One)\nB. B. (Bryan) Davis\nS. A. (Sidney) Jensen\nL. W. (Lester) Strom\nExamining Board (Vote for 3)\nM. T. (Tom) CampbellJ Incumb\u2019t)\nH. P. (Herb) Carithers (Incumb\u2019t)\nH. (Harry) Williams\nN. B. (Buck) Buchanan\nSick Committee (Vote for Three)\nA. A. (Andy) Sheridan\n(Incumbent)\nR. C. (Ronny) Willits (Incumb\u2019t)\nR. R. (Ray) Waters\nD. (David) Hollander\nFlorida State Pipe Trades Council\n(Vote for Two)\nD. T. (Dave) Dobbs (Incumbent)\nG. T. (George) Fitzpatrick\nS. M. (Sam) Bloom\nN. (Nate) Goldy\nS. W. (Sam) Long\nR. W. (Bob) Warden\nA. A. (Andy) Sheridan\npanies, the CWA went on record\nfavoring passage of the $1.2 bil\nlion school construction bill; major\nrevision in the social security law;\nreduction of interest rates for\nFil A housing, and appropriation of\n$5 billion yearly for slum clear\nance and urban redevelopment.\nBeirne Assail* Ike\nKeynoting the convention, Pres.\nJoseph A. Beirne assailed Eisen\nhower for having been reluctant\nto acknowledge the seriousness of\nthe economic situation, and then\nfor his reluctance to act to correct\nthe worsening recession.\nBeirne was critical of the Ad\nministration for being \u201ccontrolled\nby business interests\u201d who, he said,\n\u201cbrought this recession to this\ncountry deliberately,\u201d declaring\nthat \u201cthis is a crime of the highest\norder.\u201d\nAFL-CIO Sec.-Treas. William\nF. Schnitzler also turned his wrath\non the Eisenhower Administration,\ntelling the CWA convention that\nthe White House was indulging in\n\u201cdeliberate juggling of unemploy\nment figures\u201d in order to \u201cmake\nthe public forget the misery and\nsuffering that human beings are\nenduring because of the recession.\u201d\nMembership Grows\nThe executive board\u2019s annual re\nport showed CWA membership at\nan all time high of more than 276,-\n000, continuing the steady growth\nwhich has marked the 20-year per\niod since the union was first or\nganized as the National Federation\nof Telephone Workers. The union\nrepresents telephone workers in 46\nstates, Hawaii and three Canadian\nprovinces.\nContracts providing wage in\ncreases totaling over $63.5 million\nwere negotiated by the union last\nyear, the report continued, with\nthe collective bargaining sessions\nalso highlighted by negotiation of\nwell over $1 billion worth of in\nsurance for members working at\nAssociated Bell Co. and Western\nElectric.\nIn a spirited overtime session\nmarked by numerous attempts to\npostpone action or make it the sub\nject of a referendum, the conven\ntion overturned, by a narrow mar\ngin, a motion to increase the per\ncapita dues to the international\nfrom $1.50 to $2.00 a month.\nThis followed on the heels of\nearlier action by the convention\nin defeating three separate consti\ntutional amendments aimed at dis\nciplining officers or members\ncharged with disloyalty to the un\nion through such acts as \u201cencour\naging members to resign, encour\naging members to join unions oth\ner than CWA discouraging per\nsons from joining CWA.\u201d\nIn other convention action, dele\ngates approved resolutions:\nI\u2014Expanding the union\u2019s edu\ncational program and cooperating\nwith university educational pro\ngrams.\n2\u2014Calling for abolition of the\nnational origins quota in the Mc-\nCarran-Walter Immigration Act.\n3\u2014Supporting the principles of\nthe United Nations.\n(Continued on Page 4)\nPrice: Five Cents","height":"27600","width":"18565"}}
